R.

1092
01:18:51,715 --> 01:18:53,466
My God, you did it.

1093
01:18:54,050 --> 01:18:57,887
You just defeated Nazism
with a crossword puzzle.

1094
01:18:57,971 --> 01:18:59,388
There are five people
in the world

1095
01:18:59,473 --> 01:19:01,015
who know the position
of every ship in the Atlantic.

1096
01:19:01,975 --> 01:19:04,477
- They're all in this room.
- Oh, good God.

1097
01:19:04,561 --> 01:19:07,396
Oh, I don't think even He has
the power that we do right now.

1098
01:19:07,522 --> 01:19:10,524
No, there's going to be an attack
on a British passenger convoy.

1099
01:19:11,234 --> 01:19:12,985
- Right there.
- Oh, God, you're right.

1100
01:19:13,069 --> 01:19:15,321
All those U-boats
are only 20, 30 minutes away.

1101
01:19:15,405 --> 01:19:17,656
Civilians. Hundreds of them.
We can save their lives.

1102
01:19:17,741 --> 01:19:19,158
I'll phone Denniston's office

1103
01:19:19,242 --> 01:19:20,659
- so that he can alert the Admiralty.
- No.

1104
01:19:20,744 --> 01:19:21,911
Do you think there's enough time
to save them?

1105
01:19:21,995 --> 01:19:23,662
There should be if we can get
a message to that convoy.

1106
01:19:23,747 --> 01:19:25,498
Commander Denniston's office, please.
It's urgent.

1107
01:19:25,582 --> 01:19:28,000
- No.
- What the hell are you doing?

1108
01:19:28,084 --> 01:19:29,835
You... You... You can't call Denniston.

1109
01:19:29,920 --> 01:19:32,087
You... You can't tell him
about the attack.

1110
01:19:32,172 --> 01:19:33,589
What are you talking about?

1111
01:19:33,673 --> 01:19:35,341
We can have air support
over that convoy in 10 minutes.

1112
01:19:35,425 --> 01:19:37,927
- Let the U-boat sink the convoy.
- Look, it's been a big day,

1113
01:19:38,053 --> 01:19:39,845
maybe you're suffering
from a bit of shock...

1114
01:19:39,930 --> 01:19:41,847
- We don't have time for this.
- No!

1115
01:19:44,100 --> 01:19:45,935
- That's enough! That's enough!
- Stop, Hugh!

1116
01:19:46,061 --> 01:19:47,436
John, the attack is in minutes.

1117
01:19:49,189 --> 01:19:50,689
Yes, no, I'm fine. I'm fine.

1118
01:19:51,191 --> 01:19:52,608
I'm fine.

1119
01:19:54,069 --> 01:19:56,028
Do you know why
people like violence, Hugh?

1120
01:19:57,781 --> 01:19:59,907
It's because it feels good.

1121
01:20:01,409 --> 01:20:05,704
Sometimes we can't do what feels good.
We have to do what is logical.

1122
01:20:06,289 --> 01:20:07,456
What's logical?

1123
01:20:08,124 --> 01:20:11,126
Hardest time to lie to somebody
is when they're expecting to be lied to.

1124
01:20:11,795 --> 01:20:14,129
- Oh, God.
- What?

1125
01:20:14,256 --> 01:20:17,299
If someone's waiting for a lie,
you can't just, er, give them one.

1126
01:20:18,969 --> 01:20:20,636
Oh, damn it, Alan's right.

1127
01:20:21,638 --> 01:20:23,055
What?

1128
01:20:23,139 --> 01:20:26,976
What would the Germans think
if we destroy their U-boats?

1129
01:20:27,060 --> 01:20:28,727
Nothing. They'll be dead.

1130
01:20:28,812 --> 01:20:32,231
No. No, you can't be right.

1131
01:20:32,315 --> 01:20:35,568
So our convoy suddenly veers off course.

1132
01:20:36,611 --> 01:20:38,404
A squadron of RAF bombers

1133
01:20:38,488 --> 01:20:41,991
miraculously descends on
the coordinates of the U-boats.

1134
01:20:43,159 --> 01:20:45,911
What will the Germans think?

1135
01:20:48,248 --> 01:20:51,500
The Germans will know
that we have broken Enigma.

1136
01:20:52,002 --> 01:20:55,588
They'll stop all radio
communications by midday

1137
01:20:55,672 --> 01:20:58,090
and they'll have changed
the design of Enigma by the weekend.

1138
01:20:58,174 --> 01:20:59,633
Yes.

1139
01:21:00,969 --> 01:21:02,428
Two years' work.

1140
01:21:03,263 --> 01:21:06,265
Everything that we've done here,
it will all be for nothing.

1141
01:21:07,767 --> 01:21:09,852
There are
500 civilians in that convoy.

1142
01:21:10,770 --> 01:21:12,479
Women, children.

1143
01:21:14,190 --> 01:21:15,608
We're about to let them die.

1144
01:21:15,692 --> 01:21:19,278
Our job is not to save
one passenger convoy,

1145
01:21:19,362 --> 01:21:21,280
it is to win the war.

1146
01:21:21,364 --> 01:21:24,491
- Our job was to crack Enigma.
- Well, we've done that.

1147
01:21:26,369 --> 01:21:28,037
Now for the hard part.

1148
01:21:29,831 --> 01:21:31,790
- Keeping it a secret.
- Carlisle.

1149
01:21:32,876 --> 01:21:34,543
What?

1150
01:21:34,628 --> 01:21:37,212
The convoy you're about to...
It's, er...

1151
01:21:37,339 --> 01:21:39,673
The HMS Carlisle is one of the ships.

1152
01:21:41,801 --> 01:21:44,219
We can't act on every
piece of intelligence.

1153
01:21:44,346 --> 01:21:45,888
So, fine, we won't.

1154
01:21:46,973 --> 01:21:48,390
Just this one.

1155
01:21:48,808 --> 01:21:50,643
Peter, what's the matter with you?

1156
01:21:51,686 --> 01:21:53,395
My... My brother's...

1157
01:21:53,521 --> 01:21:55,397
Well, he's on the Carlisle.

1158
01:21:57,901 --> 01:21:59,568
A gunnery ensign.

1159
01:22:02,697 --> 01:22:04,073
I'm...

1160
01:22:06,242 --> 01:22:07,701
I'm so sorry.

1161
01:22:10,413 --> 01:22:12,706
Who the hell do you think you are?

1162
01:22:13,541 --> 01:22:14,917
This... This is my brother.

1163
01:22:17,420 --> 01:22:18,837
Look, he's my big brother, all right?

1164
01:22:18,922 --> 01:22:20,506
And you have a few minutes
to call off his murder.

1165
01:22:21,508 --> 01:22:23,384
We can't.

1166
01:22:25,095 --> 01:22:26,553
He's right.

1167
01:22:27,722 --> 01:22:29,181
Alan...

1168
01:22:30,100 --> 01:22:31,558
Joan...

1169
01:22:33,436 --> 01:22:35,437
Hugh... John.

1170
01:22:37,607 --> 01:22:39,608
Oh, please, I...

1171
01:22:39,693 --> 01:22:41,527
The Germans, they won't get suspicious

1172
01:22:41,611 --> 01:22:43,112
just because we stop one attack.

1173
01:22:43,697 --> 01:22:45,114
No one will know.

1174
01:22:46,074 --> 01:22:48,575
I'm asking you as your friend.

1175
01:22:50,203 --> 01:22:51,620
Please.

1176
01:22:55,291 --> 01:22:56,750
I'm so sorry.

1177
01:22:58,128 --> 01:23:01,380
You're not God, Alan, you don't
get to decide who lives and who dies.

1178
01:23:02,382 --> 01:23:03,757
Yes, we do.

1179
01:23:07,095 --> 01:23:08,303
Why?

1180
01:23:08,430 --> 01:23:10,723
Because no one else can.

1181
01:23:59,105 --> 01:24:00,522
Why are you telling me this?

1182
01:24:01,858 --> 01:24:07,029
We need your help to keep this a secret
from Admiralty, Army, RAF.

1183
01:24:08,865 --> 01:24:13,660
No one can know we broke Enigma.
Not even Denniston.

1184
01:24:14,704 --> 01:24:16,663
Who's in the process
of having you fired.

1185
01:24:17,123 --> 01:24:18,540
You can take care of that.

1186
01:24:19,167 --> 01:24:21,293
While we develop a system
to help you determine

1187
01:24:21,377 --> 01:24:24,379
how much intelligence to act on.

1188
01:24:24,464 --> 01:24:26,840
Which, er, attacks to stop,
which to let through.

1189
01:24:27,550 --> 01:24:29,384
Statistical analysis.

1190
01:24:29,469 --> 01:24:33,138
The minimal number of actions
it would take for us to win the war

1191
01:24:34,390 --> 01:24:38,811
but the maximum number we can take
before the Germans get suspicious.

1192
01:24:39,562 --> 01:24:42,731
And you're going to
trust all this to statistics?

1193
01:24:44,234 --> 01:24:45,734
- To maths?
- Correct.

1194
01:24:45,819 --> 01:24:49,404
And then MI6 can come up with
the lies that we tell everybody else.

1195
01:24:49,489 --> 01:24:51,657
You'll need a believable
alternative source

1196
01:24:51,741 --> 01:24:54,326
for all the pieces
of information you use.

1197
01:24:54,410 --> 01:24:56,495
A false story so that we can explain

1198
01:24:56,579 --> 01:24:59,498
how we got our information
that has nothing to do with Enigma.

1199
01:24:59,582 --> 01:25:02,668
And then you can leak those
stories to the, er, the Germans.

1200
01:25:02,752 --> 01:25:04,336
And then to our own military.

1201
01:25:10,593 --> 01:25:14,680
Maintain a conspiracy of lies
at the highest levels of government?

1202
01:25:23,189 --> 01:25:24,857
Sounds right up my alley.

1203
01:25:28,778 --> 01:25:32,114
Alan, I so rarely
have cause to say this,

1204
01:25:32,198 --> 01:25:35,617
but you are exactly the man
I always hoped you would be.

1205
01:25:49,632 --> 01:25:52,467
They codenamed it Ultra.

1206
01:25:52,594 --> 01:25:57,055
It became the largest store
of military intelligence

1207
01:25:57,140 --> 01:25:58,765
in the history of the world.

1208
01:26:05,815 --> 01:26:08,817
It was like having a tap
on Himmler's intercom.

1209
01:26:09,652 --> 01:26:11,111
I-E-O...

1210
01:26:12,447 --> 01:26:13,822
T-X-X...

1211
01:26:13,948 --> 01:26:16,158
Secrecy became
the primary concern

1212
01:26:16,242 --> 01:26:19,119
and for some reason, they...
They trusted me.

1213
01:26:20,997 --> 01:26:25,500
Peter, do you have the, er...
the 6:30 decrypt?

1214
01:27:06,209 --> 01:27:07,709
It's a Beale cipher.

1215
01:27:07,835 --> 01:27:09,294
Encrypted with a phrase from a...

1216
01:27:09,379 --> 01:27:12,214
"Ask, and it shall be given
to you; seek and ye will find."

1217
01:27:12,298 --> 01:27:14,716
Matthew 7:7. That was the key.

1218
01:27:14,842 --> 01:27:17,052
Peter will come around eventually.

1219
01:27:25,728 --> 01:27:27,562
Jack?

1220
01:27:27,647 --> 01:27:29,564
Could you give Alan
and me a moment, please?

1221
01:27:41,494 --> 01:27:44,371
The Soviets and us,
we're on the same side.

1222
01:27:45,373 --> 01:27:47,916
What I'm doing will help Britain.

1223
01:27:48,042 --> 01:27:50,544
I have to tell Denniston.

1224
01:27:51,587 --> 01:27:52,838
No, you don't.

1225
01:27:54,173 --> 01:27:56,258
Because if you tell him my secret,

1226
01:27:57,260 --> 01:27:58,593
I'll tell him yours.

1227
01:28:01,097 --> 01:28:03,682
Do you know what they do to homosexuals?

1228
01:28:04,934 --> 01:28:07,936
You'll never be able to work again.
Never be able to teach.

1229
01:28:08,062 --> 01:28:09,438
Your precious machine?

1230
01:28:10,606 --> 01:28:12,607
I doubt you'll ever see him again.

1231
01:28:28,791 --> 01:28:30,125
Hello. Can I...

1232
01:28:30,209 --> 01:28:33,045
um, speak to Stewart Menzies,
please? It's urgent.

1233
01:28:33,129 --> 01:28:35,047
One moment, please.

1234
01:28:38,468 --> 01:28:39,968
Hello. Menzies.

1235
01:28:43,389 --> 01:28:46,266
Some advice
about keeping secrets.

1236
01:28:48,811 --> 01:28:52,481
It's a lot easier if you
don't know them in the first place.

1237
01:28:53,649 --> 01:28:57,903
Were they steaming my letters,
tapping my telephone?

1238
01:28:57,987 --> 01:29:00,238
Trailing my nervous walks?

1239
01:29:01,449 --> 01:29:02,741
You know, I...

1240
01:29:03,826 --> 01:29:05,660
I never did find out.

1241
01:29:06,496 --> 01:29:07,954
Joan?

1242
01:29:12,293 --> 01:29:13,960
Joan? What's...

1243
01:29:16,923 --> 01:29:19,132
Oh. Where's Joan?

1244
01:29:20,676 --> 01:29:22,302
Military prison.

1245
01:29:24,847 --> 01:29:26,765
What have you done?

1246
01:29:26,849 --> 01:29:28,350
Decoded Enigma intercepts.

1247
01:29:28,476 --> 01:29:30,268
I found a pile of them
in the bedside table.

1248
01:29:30,353 --> 01:29:33,522
No, no. I... I gave those to her
over a year ago

1249
01:29:33,648 --> 01:29:35,440
when I was trying to figure out

1250
01:29:35,525 --> 01:29:37,359
- a link between...
- I'm sure you did.

1251
01:29:37,485 --> 01:29:39,444
Denniston's been looking
for a Soviet spy.

1252
01:29:39,529 --> 01:29:40,987
He's been looking inside Hut 8.

1253
01:29:43,032 --> 01:29:44,449
I know who the spy is.

1254
01:29:46,160 --> 01:29:47,994
It... It's not Joan. It's...

1255
01:29:49,705 --> 01:29:51,790
It's Cairncross.

1256
01:29:51,874 --> 01:29:55,001
I... I found the Beale cipher,
the Bible.

1257
01:29:56,379 --> 01:29:58,672
God, I wish you'd been the spy.

1258
01:30:00,341 --> 01:30:02,134
You'd be so much better
at this than he is.

1259
01:30:03,845 --> 01:30:05,637
You knew it was him?

1260
01:30:05,721 --> 01:30:07,556
Of course I bloody knew.

1261
01:30:07,640 --> 01:30:09,724
I knew before he came to Bletchley.

1262
01:30:10,643 --> 01:30:12,144
Why do you think I had him placed here?

1263
01:30:12,228 --> 01:30:14,855
But we have an Enigma machine.

1264
01:30:15,189 --> 01:30:16,481
Yes, Polish Intelligence smuggled...

1265
01:30:16,566 --> 01:30:17,983
So what's the problem?

1266
01:30:18,067 --> 01:30:22,571
You placed a...
a Soviet agent at Bletchley Park?

1267
01:30:22,655 --> 01:30:25,866
It's really quite useful to be able to
leak whatever we want to Stalin.

1268
01:30:27,660 --> 01:30:29,911
Churchill's too damn paranoid.

1269
01:30:29,996 --> 01:30:33,915
He won't share a shred
of intelligence with the Soviets.

1270
01:30:34,041 --> 01:30:36,334
Not even information that
will help them against the Germans.

1271
01:30:36,419 --> 01:30:39,254
There's... so much secrecy.

1272
01:30:41,174 --> 01:30:44,176
Cairncross has no idea
we know, of course.

1273
01:30:44,260 --> 01:30:46,761
He's really not the brightest bulb.

1274
01:30:48,222 --> 01:30:50,432
Which is why I need your help.

1275
01:30:50,558 --> 01:30:52,184
I want to know what to leak to John,

1276
01:30:52,268 --> 01:30:54,936
what to feed to the Soviets
as well as the British.

1277
01:30:55,062 --> 01:30:56,521
I...

1278
01:30:57,106 --> 01:30:59,566
I'm not a... I'm not a spy. I'm...

1279
01:31:00,359 --> 01:31:02,944
I'm just a mathematician.

1280
01:31:03,029 --> 01:31:05,113
I know a lot of spies, Alan.

1281
01:31:06,365 --> 01:31:09,367
You've got more secrets
than the best of them.

1282
01:31:13,706 --> 01:31:17,209
You... You have to promise me
that you will release Joan.

1283
01:31:18,044 --> 01:31:19,461
Yes, Joan's at the market.

1284
01:31:19,545 --> 01:31:21,796
She's going to be back
in an hour. I lied.

1285
01:31:23,966 --> 01:31:25,800
I'd better hold on to these.

1286
01:31:25,927 --> 01:31:29,763
If anybody finds out about them,
prison will be the least of her worries.

1287
01:31:32,266 --> 01:31:33,642
Oh, Alan,

1288
01:31:35,102 --> 01:31:37,729
we're going to have
such a wonderful war together.

1289
01:31:57,166 --> 01:31:58,750
I need you to leave Bletchley.

1290
01:31:58,834 --> 01:31:59,918
What?

1291
01:32:00,002 --> 01:32:02,420
It's Menzies.
I don't trust him.

1292
01:32:02,505 --> 01:32:04,172
It's not safe here.

1293
01:32:04,257 --> 01:32:05,840
Do you think
it's any safer anywhere else?

1294
01:32:05,925 --> 01:32:08,343
You need to get away.
You need to get very far away from me.

1295
01:32:08,427 --> 01:32:09,844
Alan, what's happened?

1296
01:32:14,350 --> 01:32:16,935
We can't be engaged any more. You...

1297
01:32:17,019 --> 01:32:20,522
Your parents need to take you back
and find you a husband elsewhere.

1298
01:32:22,441 --> 01:32:24,526
What's wrong with you?

1299
01:32:25,486 --> 01:32:28,321
I have something, er, to tell you.

1300
01:32:28,698 --> 01:32:29,864
I'm...

1301
01:32:33,035 --> 01:32:34,661
I'm a homosexual.

1302
01:32:37,790 --> 01:32:40,875
- All right.
- No, no. Men, Joan.

1303
01:32:42,628 --> 01:32:44,379
- Not women.
- So what?

1304
01:32:45,548 --> 01:32:47,048
Well, I... I just told you.

1305
01:32:47,174 --> 01:32:48,550
So what?

1306
01:32:51,721 --> 01:32:53,888
I had my suspicions, I always did.

1307
01:32:55,224 --> 01:32:59,060
But we're not like other people.
We love each other in our own way

1308
01:32:59,186 --> 01:33:01,229
and we can have the life together
that we want.

1309
01:33:01,355 --> 01:33:03,690
You... You won't be the perfect husband.

1310
01:33:04,650 --> 01:33:07,902
Well, I can promise you, I harbour
no intention of being the perfect wife.

1311
01:33:07,987 --> 01:33:12,490
I'll not be fixing your lamb all day
while you come home from the office.

1312
01:33:12,575 --> 01:33:14,075
I'll work.

1313
01:33:14,994 --> 01:33:16,411
You'll work.

1314
01:33:18,080 --> 01:33:20,081
And we'll have each other's company.

1315
01:33:20,916 --> 01:33:23,209
We'll have each other's minds.

1316
01:33:23,711 --> 01:33:26,379
That sounds like a better
marriage than most.

1317
01:33:28,758 --> 01:33:30,383
Because I care for you.

1318
01:33:31,927 --> 01:33:33,511
And you care for me.

1319
01:33:35,598 --> 01:33:37,265
And we understand
one another more than...

1320
01:33:37,350 --> 01:33:39,768
more than anyone else ever has.

1321
01:33:41,604 --> 01:33:43,021
I don't.

1322
01:33:46,776 --> 01:33:48,401
- What?
- Care for you.

1323
01:33:49,278 --> 01:33:50,695
I never did.

1324
01:33:50,780 --> 01:33:53,782
I... I just needed you to break Enigma.

1325
01:33:53,908 --> 01:33:56,701
I've done that now, so... So you can go.

1326
01:34:02,541 --> 01:34:04,584
I'm not going anywhere.

1327
01:34:05,920 --> 01:34:07,712
I've spent entirely too much of my life

1328
01:34:07,797 --> 01:34:09,297
worried about what you think of me

1329
01:34:09,382 --> 01:34:11,299
or what my parents think of me

1330
01:34:11,384 --> 01:34:13,468
or the boys in Hut 8
or the girls in Hut 3.

1331
01:34:13,552 --> 01:34:15,136
And do you know what? I'm done.

1332
01:34:16,722 --> 01:34:19,974
This is the most important
work I will ever do

1333
01:34:20,059 --> 01:34:23,436
and no one is going to stop me,
least of all you.

1334
01:34:26,315 --> 01:34:28,733
Do you know what? They were right.

1335
01:34:29,652 --> 01:34:31,820
Peter, Hugh, John.

1336
01:34:35,449 --> 01:34:37,075
You really are a monster.

1337
01:34:56,053 --> 01:35:00,765
The war dragged on
for two more solitary years

1338
01:35:03,185 --> 01:35:06,896
and every day we performed
our blood-soaked calculus.

1339
01:35:09,150 --> 01:35:12,485
Every day we decided
who lived and who died.

1340
01:35:12,570 --> 01:35:17,407
Every day we helped the Allies
to victories and nobody knew.

1341
01:35:21,620 --> 01:35:23,079
Stalingrad.

1342
01:35:23,956 --> 01:35:26,875
The Ardenne. The invasion of Normandy.

1343
01:35:28,043 --> 01:35:30,211
All victories that would not
have been possible

1344
01:35:30,296 --> 01:35:32,422
without the intelligence
that we supplied.

1345
01:35:33,799 --> 01:35:36,718
And people talk about the war

1346
01:35:36,802 --> 01:35:40,763
as this epic battle
between civilisations.

1347
01:35:42,600 --> 01:35:46,019
Freedom versus tyranny.
Democracy versus Nazism.

1348
01:35:47,688 --> 01:35:51,816
Armies of millions
bleeding into the ground.

1349
01:35:51,901 --> 01:35:55,069
Fleets of ships
weighing down the oceans.

1350
01:35:55,154 --> 01:35:59,073
Planes dropping bombs from the sky
until they obliterated the sun itself.

1351
01:36:01,202 --> 01:36:03,620
The war wasn't like that for us.

1352
01:36:06,665 --> 01:36:08,124
For us it was just...

1353
01:36:10,085 --> 01:36:12,045
half a dozen crossword enthusiasts

1354
01:36:12,129 --> 01:36:14,631
in a tiny village
in the South of England.

1355
01:36:17,760 --> 01:36:19,511
...your victory.

1356
01:36:19,595 --> 01:36:21,054
It is the victory

1357
01:36:22,306 --> 01:36:26,601
of the cause of freedom in every land.

1358
01:36:31,023 --> 01:36:34,400
This is a solemn but glorious hour.

1359
01:36:35,861 --> 01:36:40,281
I wish that Franklin D Roosevelt
had lived to see this day.

1360
01:36:41,325 --> 01:36:42,951
Was I God? No.

1361
01:36:43,619 --> 01:36:46,329
Because God didn't
win the war,

1362
01:36:47,706 --> 01:36:49,165
we did.

1363
01:37:01,679 --> 01:37:03,638
So what happens now?

1364
01:37:05,266 --> 01:37:08,476
Is it back to university for us,
I suppose?

1365
01:37:09,270 --> 01:37:10,687
Yes, pretty much.

1366
01:37:10,771 --> 01:37:12,355
But you've one other thing left to do

1367
01:37:12,439 --> 01:37:14,649
before your service
to your government is concluded.

1368
01:37:14,733 --> 01:37:17,652
- What's that?
- Burn everything.

1369
01:37:17,736 --> 01:37:19,195
Burn? Why?

1370
01:37:19,280 --> 01:37:22,323
You were told when you started
this was a top secret programme.

1371
01:37:22,408 --> 01:37:24,033
Did you think we were joking?

1372
01:37:24,868 --> 01:37:26,327
But the war is over.

1373
01:37:26,412 --> 01:37:28,663
This war is.
But there'll be others.

1374
01:37:28,747 --> 01:37:31,082
And we know how to break a code

1375
01:37:31,166 --> 01:37:33,793
that everybody else
believes is unbreakable.

1376
01:37:34,670 --> 01:37:36,087
Precisely.

1377
01:37:37,756 --> 01:37:39,465
Tear it down, light it up.

1378
01:37:39,550 --> 01:37:42,885
Sweep away the ashes.
None of you have ever met before.

1379
01:37:42,970 --> 01:37:46,222
None of you have ever
even heard the word "Enigma".

1380
01:37:48,475 --> 01:37:50,184
Have a safe trip home.

1381
01:37:53,647 --> 01:37:55,356
Behave.

1382
01:37:55,441 --> 01:37:57,150
With a bit of luck,
you'll never have to see me

1383
01:37:57,234 --> 01:37:59,777
or one another again
for the rest of your lives.

1384
01:38:15,294 --> 01:38:16,794
That's unbelievable.

1385
01:38:18,964 --> 01:38:20,882
Now, Detective,

1386
01:38:22,885 --> 01:38:24,552
you get to judge.

1387
01:38:27,139 --> 01:38:28,598
So tell me,

1388
01:38:30,392 --> 01:38:31,851
what am I?

1389
01:38:33,687 --> 01:38:37,523
Am I a machine? Am I a person?

1390
01:38:39,401 --> 01:38:40,985
Am I a war hero?

1391
01:38:43,656 --> 01:38:45,490
Am I a criminal?

1392
01:38:49,536 --> 01:38:51,204
I can't judge you.

1393
01:38:54,500 --> 01:38:55,958
Well, then.

1394
01:38:59,380 --> 01:39:02,298
You're no help to me at all.

1395
01:39:05,344 --> 01:39:06,928
Come in.

1396
01:39:11,308 --> 01:39:13,351
You wanted to see me, sir?

1397
01:39:13,435 --> 01:39:15,144
Turing. Sit down.

1398
01:39:27,533 --> 01:39:28,950
Is something the matter?

1399
01:39:29,952 --> 01:39:32,495
You and Christopher Morcom
are quite close.

1400
01:39:32,579 --> 01:39:34,455
I wouldn't say that.

1401
01:39:34,540 --> 01:39:36,040
Well, your mathematics teacher says

1402
01:39:36,125 --> 01:39:37,750
the two of you
are positively inseparable.

1403
01:39:37,835 --> 01:39:39,794
We're the best students in the class.

1404
01:39:40,754 --> 01:39:42,755
He caught you passing
notes the other day.

1405
01:39:42,840 --> 01:39:45,883
Cryptography, to pass the time.
The class is too simple.

1406
01:39:45,968 --> 01:39:49,846
You and your friend solve
maths problems during maths class

1407
01:39:49,930 --> 01:39:51,597
because the maths class is too dull?

1408
01:39:52,474 --> 01:39:54,183
He's not my friend.

1409
01:39:54,268 --> 01:39:57,645
- Well, I'm told he's your only friend.
- Who said that?

1410
01:40:00,774 --> 01:40:03,484
Something's come up concerning Morcom.

1411
01:40:04,319 --> 01:40:05,862
Why am I here?

1412
01:40:08,657 --> 01:40:10,408
Christopher is dead.

1413
01:40:18,959 --> 01:40:20,543
I don't understand.

1414
01:40:20,627 --> 01:40:24,672
His mother sent word this morning.
The family were on holiday, you see.

1415
01:40:29,219 --> 01:40:30,803
I don't understand.

1416
01:40:30,888 --> 01:40:34,766
Well, he had bovine tuberculosis,
as I'm sure he told you.

1417
01:40:35,976 --> 01:40:41,314
So this won't come as a shock
but still, all the same, I'm sorry.

1418
01:40:43,484 --> 01:40:45,109
You're mistaken.

1419
01:40:46,737 --> 01:40:48,196
Did he not tell you?

1420
01:40:49,406 --> 01:40:51,824
Well, he's been sick for a long time.

1421
01:40:51,909 --> 01:40:53,951
He knew this was coming soon.

1422
01:40:55,370 --> 01:40:57,205
But he had a stiff upper lip about it.

1423
01:40:57,289 --> 01:40:58,790
Good lad.

1424
01:41:00,876 --> 01:41:02,919
- Are you all right, Turing?
- Yes. Of course.

1425
01:41:03,003 --> 01:41:05,838
Like I said,
I didn't know him very well.

1426
01:41:05,923 --> 01:41:09,175
Ah, I see. Very well.

1427
01:41:13,680 --> 01:41:16,057
May I leave, Headmaster?

1428
01:41:30,280 --> 01:41:32,073
Congratulations, sir.

1429
01:41:59,768 --> 01:42:01,227
Sorry.

1430
01:42:05,732 --> 01:42:08,734
I would have come.
I would have testified.

1431
01:42:09,903 --> 01:42:13,698
And what would you have said?
That I... I wasn't a homosexual?

1432
01:42:13,782 --> 01:42:17,243
Alan, this is serious.
They could send you to jail.

1433
01:42:17,327 --> 01:42:18,744
Oh, damn it.

1434
01:42:22,082 --> 01:42:25,167
- Your hands, you're twitching.
- No. No, I'm not.

1435
01:42:25,252 --> 01:42:26,669
- Alan.
- Er...

1436
01:42:28,839 --> 01:42:30,590
It's the medication.

1437
01:42:31,758 --> 01:42:33,175
The medication?

1438
01:42:34,595 --> 01:42:38,222
Well, the judge gave me, um, a choice.

1439
01:42:38,307 --> 01:42:42,476
Either two years in prison or
hor... hormonal therapy.

1440
01:42:42,561 --> 01:42:43,978
Oh, my God.

1441
01:42:45,022 --> 01:42:47,440
- Oh, my God!
- Yes, yes, that's right.

1442
01:42:47,524 --> 01:42:50,067
Chemical castration.

1443
01:42:50,152 --> 01:42:54,113
To, er, to cure me of my, um,
homosexual predilections.

1444
01:42:55,908 --> 01:42:58,409
Well, of course I chose that.
I mean, I couldn't...

1445
01:42:59,745 --> 01:43:01,746
work in prison and...

1446
01:43:02,748 --> 01:43:04,165
All right.

1447
01:43:06,001 --> 01:43:07,919
Now, I'm going to speak to your doctors.

1448
01:43:08,003 --> 01:43:10,755
- I'm going to speak to your lawyers.
- I'm... I'm fine.

1449
01:43:10,839 --> 01:43:12,590
- Please let me help you.
- No, I...

1450
01:43:12,674 --> 01:43:15,134
I don't need your help, thank you.

1451
01:43:15,677 --> 01:43:17,553
Alan, you do not have to do this alone.

1452
01:43:18,889 --> 01:43:20,473
I'm not alone.

1453
01:43:24,144 --> 01:43:25,728
Never have been.

1454
01:43:30,233 --> 01:43:32,693
Christopher's become so smart.

1455
01:43:35,906 --> 01:43:40,034
If I don't continue
my treatment, then they'll...

1456
01:43:43,747 --> 01:43:46,540
They'll take him away from me.

1457
01:43:47,292 --> 01:43:48,709
You...

1458
01:43:51,672 --> 01:43:55,508
You... You... You can't let them
do that. You can't.

1459
01:43:56,677 --> 01:43:59,470
You... You can't let them
leave me alone.

1460
01:44:02,641 --> 01:44:04,308
I don't... I don't want to be alone.

1461
01:44:04,393 --> 01:44:05,893
I don't want to be alone.

1462
01:44:05,978 --> 01:44:07,895
All right, all right.

1463
01:44:07,980 --> 01:44:09,981
All right.

1464
01:44:10,983 --> 01:44:13,109
It's all right, come and sit down.

1465
01:44:16,488 --> 01:44:18,614
It's all right. Come and sit down.

1466
01:44:22,494 --> 01:44:23,953
It's all right.

1467
01:44:34,548 --> 01:44:38,009
Oh, well...

1468
01:44:38,093 --> 01:44:41,387
That's a much nicer ring
than the one I... I made you.

1469
01:44:41,471 --> 01:44:43,139
Yes.

1470
01:44:43,223 --> 01:44:44,974
His name's Jock.

1471
01:44:45,058 --> 01:44:47,810
He's an army man,
if you can believe it.

1472
01:44:47,894 --> 01:44:50,312
We work together.

1473
01:44:53,400 --> 01:44:55,943
Why don't we do a crossword puzzle?

1474
01:44:57,279 --> 01:44:59,155
It'll only take us five minutes.

1475
01:44:59,239 --> 01:45:00,781
Or in your case, six.

1476
01:45:05,871 --> 01:45:07,288
There.

1477
01:45:30,771 --> 01:45:32,772
Perhaps later.

1478
01:45:34,107 --> 01:45:35,566
Yes, of course.

1479
01:45:41,490 --> 01:45:43,574
You got what you wanted, didn't you?

1480
01:45:44,701 --> 01:45:46,285
Work, a husband.

1481
01:45:47,621 --> 01:45:49,080
Normal life.

1482
01:45:59,466 --> 01:46:01,967
No one normal could have done that.

1483
01:46:06,056 --> 01:46:08,099
Do you know, this morning,

1484
01:46:09,267 --> 01:46:13,604
I was on a train that went
through a city that wouldn't exist

1485
01:46:13,688 --> 01:46:15,689
if it wasn't for you.

1486
01:46:17,359 --> 01:46:21,737
I bought a ticket from a man
who would likely be dead

1487
01:46:21,822 --> 01:46:24,073
if it wasn't for you.

1488
01:46:24,157 --> 01:46:25,991
I read up on my work,

1489
01:46:27,369 --> 01:46:30,913
a whole field of scientific inquiry

1490
01:46:30,997 --> 01:46:34,041
that only exists because of you.

1491
01:46:37,212 --> 01:46:40,172
Now, if you wish
you could have been normal,

1492
01:46:42,509 --> 01:46:44,718
I can promise you, I do not.

1493
01:46:46,888 --> 01:46:49,682
The world is an infinitely better place

1494
01:46:49,766 --> 01:46:52,101
precisely because you weren't.

1495
01:46:55,897 --> 01:46:57,314
Do you...

1496
01:46:58,066 --> 01:46:59,900
Do you really think that?

1497
01:47:01,444 --> 01:47:02,903
I think

1498
01:47:04,072 --> 01:47:07,867
that sometimes it is the people
who no one imagines anything of

1499
01:47:07,951 --> 01:47:12,496
who do the things
that no one can imagine.
